
CPU Scheduling & Process Execution (Linux Internals)

Everything that runs on Linux is a **process competing for CPU time**.

If you deeply understand this part, tools like `top`, `pidstat`, `perf`, `strace` will suddenly make **perfect sense**.

---

# 1️⃣ First Principle: CPU Is a Limited Resource

Your system:

```
8 CPU cores
```

Meaning **8 processes can run at the exact same time**.

If there are:

```
8 processes → all run
16 processes → 8 run, 8 must wait
```

Those waiting processes go into something called the:

```
Run Queue
```

---

# 3️⃣ Process States (Real Kernel Behavior)

Every process in Linux is always in a **state**.

Common ones:

```
R → Running or runnable
S → Sleeping
D → Uninterruptible sleep (usually disk I/O)
Z → Zombie
```

You can see them in:

```
ps aux
```

or

```
top
```

Example:

```
PID USER STAT COMMAND
1000 root R nginx
1001 root S sshd
1002 root D postgres
```

Meaning:

```
R → on CPU or ready
S → waiting for event
D → waiting for disk
```

---

# 4️⃣ Context Switching (Critical Concept)

When many processes want CPU, Linux rapidly **switches between them**.

Example:

```
process A runs
switch
process B runs
switch
process C runs
```

This happens **thousands of times per second**.

This is called:

```
Context switch
```

Because the CPU must save:

```
registers
memory state
program counter
```

Then load another process.

---

# 5️⃣ Why Context Switching Matters

Too many switches = overhead.

Example scenario:

```
500 runnable processes
8 CPUs
```

Kernel constantly switching.

Result:

```
CPU time wasted on switching
```

Instead of doing real work.

You can measure switches:

```
vmstat 1
```

Look at:

```
cs → context switches
```

---

# 6️⃣ Time Slices (CPU Sharing)

Linux doesn't let one process hog CPU forever.

Instead:

```
process gets time slice
```

Example:

```
5 ms
```

After that:

```
scheduler may switch to another process
```

This makes Linux **fair**.

---

# 7️⃣ Linux Scheduler

Modern Linux uses:

```
CFS
```

The **Completely Fair Scheduler**.

Goal:

```
every process gets fair CPU time
```

Concept:

```
virtual runtime
```

Processes that ran less get priority.

---

# 8️⃣ Example Scheduler Behavior

Example processes:

```
A CPU heavy
B CPU heavy
C CPU heavy
```

Scheduler rotates:

```
A → B → C → A → B → C
```

But if:

```
D wakes up
```

Scheduler may run D earlier because it **hasn't run recently**.

---

# 9️⃣ Nice Values (Priority Control)

Users can influence scheduling.

Range:

```
-20 → highest priority
19 → lowest priority
```

Check:

```
ps -eo pid,ni,cmd
```

Change:

```
nice -n 10 command
```

or

```
renice
```

